Pages = {{273-282}},
Month = {{MAY-JUN}},
Abstract = {{Behavioral inhibition (BI) is a temperament characterized by heightened
   negative affect and social reticence to unfamiliar peers. In a
   longitudinal study, 291 infants were assessed for BI at 24 and 36 months
   of age. At age 7, N2 amplitude was measured during a Flanker task. Also
   at age 7, children experienced social exclusion in the lab during an
   interaction with an unfamiliar peer and an experimenter. Our findings
   indicate that children characterized as high in BI, relative to those
   low in BI, had larger (i.e., more negative) N2 amplitudes. Additionally,
   among children with a large N2, BI was positively related to withdrawal
   and negatively related to assertiveness during social exclusion. These
   findings suggest that variations in conflict detection among
   behaviorally inhibited children plays a role in their social behavior
   during stressful social situations. Copyright (c) 2014 John Wiley \&
