Abstract = {{Recent research has modified both the conceptualization and treatment of
   eating disorders. New diagnostic criteria reducing the ``not otherwise
   specified{''} category should facilitate the early recognition and
   treatment of anorexia nervosa (AN) and bulimia nervosa (BN).
   Technology-based studies identify AN and BN as ``brain circuit{''}
   disorders; epidemiologic studies reveal that the narrow racial, ethnic
   and income profile of individuals no longer holds true for AN. The major
   organs affected long term-the brain and skeletal system-both respond to
   improved nutrition, with maintenance of body weight the best predictor
   of recovery. Twin studies have revealed gene x environment interactions,
   including both the external (social) and internal (pubertal)
   environments of boys and of girls. Family-based treatment has the best
   evidence base for effectiveness for younger patients. Medication plays a
   limited role in AN, but a major role in BN. Across diagnoses, the most
   important medicine is food.}},
