Month = {{APR 16}},
Abstract = {{Humans typically discount future gains more than losses. This phenomenon
   is referred to as the ``sign effect{''} in experimental and behavioral
   economics. Although recent studies have reported associations between
   the sign effect and important social problems, such as obesity and
   incurring multiple debts, the biological basis for this phenomenon
   remains poorly understood. Here, we hypothesized that enhanced
   loss-related neural processing in magnitude and/or delay representation
   are causes of the sign effect. We examined participants performing
   intertemporal choice tasks involving future gains or losses and compared
   the brain activity of those who exhibited the sign effect and those who
   did not. When predicting future losses, significant differences were
   apparent between the two participant groups in terms of striatal
   activity representing delay length and in insular activity representing
   sensitivity to magnitude. Furthermore, participants with the sign effect
   exhibited a greater insular response to the magnitude of loss than to
   that of gain, and also a greater striatal response to the delay of loss
   than to that of gain. These findings may provide a new biological
   perspective for the development of novel treatments and preventive
   measures for social problems associated with the sign effect.}},
